# prove-it ‚Äî Strict Mode

Four gates. All must show `PASS ‚úì`. None are optional.

Use for: production features, security-sensitive code, public APIs, database migrations,
anything with direct user-visible behavior.

---

## Gate 1 ‚Äî Compile / Type Check

Show the build is clean before running any tests.

```
GATE 1 ‚Äî COMPILE
‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
Command: [tsc --noEmit | cargo build | go build ./... | mvn compile -q | go vet ./...]
Output:  [paste output ‚Äî empty output means clean]
Status:  PASS ‚úì
```

Language-specific Gate 1 commands:
- **TypeScript:** `npx tsc --noEmit`
- **Go:** `go build ./... && go vet ./...`
- **Rust:** `cargo build` (cargo test includes this ‚Äî run separately for clarity)
- **Java/Maven:** `mvn compile -q`
- **Java/Gradle:** `./gradlew compileJava`

---

## Gate 2 ‚Äî Regression (existing test suite)

The full existing test suite must pass. Zero regressions from this change.

```
GATE 2 ‚Äî REGRESSION
‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
Command: [full test suite command]
Output:  [paste output ‚Äî show total pass count]
Status:  PASS ‚úì (N tests, 0 failures)
```

### Pre-existing failures

If the suite was already failing before your change, you must document it:

```
Pre-existing failure: [test name]
Cause: [known issue / unrelated to this change]
Evidence: [this test was failing on main before this branch]
```

Do NOT claim Gate 2 passes if pre-existing failures exist without documentation.
Do NOT hide pre-existing failures by skipping them.

---

## Gate 3 ‚Äî New Tests

New behavior requires new tests. Show them passing.

```
GATE 3 ‚Äî NEW TESTS
‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
Tests added: [list test names or file path]
Command:     [run new tests ‚Äî filter to new tests if possible, else full suite]
Output:      [paste passing output]
Status:      PASS ‚úì (M new tests)
```

If you cannot add tests (read-only test dir, external dependency with no test interface):
document why and describe what manual verification covers it.

---

## Gate 4 ‚Äî Edge Cases

For every function added or modified, identify and handle:

| Category         | Example                                     |
|------------------|---------------------------------------------|
| Null / nil       | `null`, `undefined`, `nil`, `None`          |
| Empty collection | `[]`, `{}`, `""`, `0`                       |
| Boundary values  | `INT_MAX`, `INT_MIN`, single-element lists  |
| Error path       | network failure, invalid input, timeout     |
| Concurrent access| if the code touches shared state            |

```
GATE 4 ‚Äî EDGE CASES
‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
Tested:     [list each case that has a test]
Documented: [list each case intentionally skipped, with reason]
```

It is acceptable to document rather than test edge cases when:
- The case is impossible given upstream validation (state the validation)
- The case is handled by a tested library function (name the function)
- Testing requires significant infrastructure not worth the scope (acknowledge the risk)

Silently omitting edge cases is not acceptable.

---

## Strict Done

Only say done after all four gates show `PASS ‚úì`:

```
STRICT DONE
‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
Gate 1 (compile):    PASS ‚úì
Gate 2 (regression): PASS ‚úì (N tests)
Gate 3 (new tests):  PASS ‚úì (M new tests)
Gate 4 (edges):      PASS ‚úì (K tested, J documented)
```

If any gate is `FAIL ‚úó`: stop. Fix the gate. Re-run. Show the new output.

---

## Activation

This rule is not `alwaysApply`. Enable it in Cursor's rules panel or type `/prove-it strict`.
Disable with `/prove-it verify` to return to default mode.

Not sure which mode to use?
- Prototypes / spikes ‚Üí `/prove-it off`
- Day-to-day coding ‚Üí `verify` (default, always on)
- New features / bug fixes ‚Üí `/prove-it tdd`
- Production / security / APIs ‚Üí `/prove-it strict` (this file)
